ds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=MPyLmcmesao:XX7Zmf_zjEg:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a>\n</div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Techcrunch/~4/MPyLmcmesao\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>]]></content:encoded>\r\n\t\t\t<wfw:commentRss>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/motorola-buys-connected-home-and-energy-management-software-developer-4home/feed/</wfw:commentRss>\r\n\t\t<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>\r\n\t\r\n\t\t<media:content url=\"http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a5a5ed70fa7c651aa5ec9ca8de57a4b8?s=96&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G\" medium=\"image\">\r\n\t\t\t<media:title type=\"html\">leena</media:title>\r\n\t\t</media:content>\r\n\r\n\t\t<media:content url=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/4home-connected-home-services.jpg\" medium=\"image\" />\r\n\t<feedburner:origLink>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/motorola-buys-connected-home-and-energy-management-software-developer-4home/</feedburner:origLink></item>\r\n\t\t<item>\r\n\t\t<title>Ask a VC: Lightspeed’s Jeremy Liew Awaits Your Questions</title>\r\n\t\t<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/djO5cX7AUb4/</link>\r\n\t\t<comments>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/ask-a-vc-lightspeeds-jeremy-liew-awaits-your-questions/#comments</comments>\r\n\t\t<pubDate>Wed, 01 Dec 2010 22:02:28 +0000</pubDate>\r\n\t\t<dc:creator>Sarah Lacy</dc:creator>\r\n\t\t\t\t<category><![CDATA[TC]]></category>\r\n\t\t<category><![CDATA[Ask a VC]]></category>\r\n\t\t<category><![CDATA[Jeremy Liew]]></category>\r\n\t\t<category><![CDATA[lightspeed venture partners]]></category>\r\n\r\n\t\t<guid isPermaLink=\"false\">http://techcrunch.com/?p=250329</guid>\r\n\t\t<description><![CDATA[Jeremy Liew is my guest on Ask a VC this week. He&#8217;s a guy with plenty of Web battle scars. He was an early employee of CitySearch back in the mid-1990s, a senior executive at InterActive Corp. and a senior executive at AOL. (You know, before AOL was cool again.)\nHe&#8217;s been at Lightspeed Venture Partners [...]<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=techcrunch.com&amp;blog=11718616&amp;post=250329&amp;subd=tctechcrunch&amp;ref=&amp;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />]]></description>\r\n\t\t\t<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/jeremy-liew.jpeg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-250340\" title=\"Jeremy Liew\" src=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/jeremy-liew.jpeg?w=227&#038;h=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"227\" height=\"300\" /></a>Jeremy Liew is my guest on Ask a VC this week. He&#8217;s a guy with plenty of Web battle scars. He was an early employee of CitySearch back in the mid-1990s, a senior executive at InterActive Corp. and a senior executive at AOL. (You know, before AOL was <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2010/09/28/tim-armstrong-we-got-techcrunch/\">cool again</a>.)</p>\n<p>He&#8217;s been at Lightspeed Venture Partners since 2006 and his investments include Playdom, Kongregate, LivingSocial, RockYou! and Serious Business, which was acquired by Zynga.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s Liew&#8217;s first time on Ask a VC, and I have a feeling it&#8217;ll be a good one. The first time I met him was at an entrepreneur retreat. We were sitting in the back of room listening to a talk by a person who will remain nameless. Most of the audience was rapt with attention, but Liew happened to say exactly what I was thinking, <em>&#8220;This guy is full of shit; I&#8217;m outta here.&#8221; </em>If you ask Liew a question, expect an honest answer. Check out some <a href=\"http://www.lightspeedvp.com/teammember.aspx?m=27\">blog posts here</a> to jog some ideas.</p>\n<p>We tape in a few hours so send your questions to askavc(at)techcrunch(dot)com now.</p>\n<br />  <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gofacebook/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/facebook/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gotwitter/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/twitter/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250329/\" /></a> <img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=techcrunch.com&amp;blog=11718616&amp;post=250329&amp;subd=tctechcrunch&amp;ref=&amp;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />\n<p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/8Df6WU-AJssE5QetpylMp_oGs4k/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/8Df6WU-AJssE5QetpylMp_oGs4k/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/>\n<a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/8Df6WU-AJssE5QetpylMp_oGs4k/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~at/8Df6WU-AJssE5QetpylMp_oGs4k/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p><div class=\"feedflare\">\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:2mJPEYqXBVI\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?d=2mJPEYqXBVI\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:-BTjWOF_DHI\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?i=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:-BTjWOF_DHI\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:D7DqB2pKExk\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?i=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:D7DqB2pKExk\" border=\"0\"></img></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?a=djO5cX7AUb4:O3iFDR2tX-w:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/Techcrunch?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a>\n</div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Techcrunch/~4/djO5cX7AUb4\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>]]></content:encoded>\r\n\t\t\t<wfw:commentRss>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/ask-a-vc-lightspeeds-jeremy-liew-awaits-your-questions/feed/</wfw:commentRss>\r\n\t\t<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>\r\n\t\r\n\t\t<media:content url=\"http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/465ea1e765cfde73e59aacc0cf5c98ef?s=96&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G\" medium=\"image\">\r\n\t\t\t<media:title type=\"html\">sarah-lacy</media:title>\r\n\t\t</media:content>\r\n\r\n\t\t<media:content url=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/jeremy-liew.jpeg?w=227\" medium=\"image\">\r\n\t\t\t<media:title type=\"html\">Jeremy Liew</media:title>\r\n\t\t</media:content>\r\n\t<feedburner:origLink>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/ask-a-vc-lightspeeds-jeremy-liew-awaits-your-questions/</feedburner:origLink></item>\r\n\t\t<item>\r\n\t\t<title>‘Boring’ Couple Beats Google In Court, Is Awarded $1</title>\r\n\t\t<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Techcrunch/~3/357tD8gtIgM/</link>\r\n\t\t<comments>http://techcrunch.com/2010/12/01/boring-google-streetview/#comments</comments>\r\n\t\t<pubDate>Wed, 01 Dec 2010 21:45:46 +0000</pubDate>\r\n\t\t<dc:creator>Jason Kincaid</dc:creator>\r\n\t\t\t\t<category><![CDATA[TC]]></category>\r\n\t\t<category><![CDATA[google]]></category>\r\n\r\n\t\t<guid isPermaLink=\"false\">http://techcrunch.com/?p=250299</guid>\r\n\t\t<description><![CDATA[<img src=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/googleboring.png\" alt=\"\" />Back in April 2008, married couple Aaron and Christine Boring <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2008/04/04/google-damages-property-values/\">filed suit</a> against Google for \"intentional and/or grossly reckless invasion\" of their privacy, because a Street View car drove down their Private road and snapped some photos of their house.\n\nAside from giving the press an opportunity to go pun-crazy, the case has been notable for its longevity: most of the charges, which included negligence, were <a href=\"http://blog.ericgoldman.org/archives/2009/02/google_street_v.htm\">thrown out</a> in February 2009, but Boring v. Google came back for an <a href=\"http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20100201/0410537989.shtml\">encore</a> this year. The lone remaining charge? Trespassing.\n\nNow, over two and a half years after the case got started, a judge has handed down her consent judgement, ruling that that Google was indeed guilty of Count II Trespass. The Borings are getting a grand total of $1 for their trouble. Ouch.<img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=techcrunch.com&amp;blog=11718616&amp;post=250299&amp;subd=tctechcrunch&amp;ref=&amp;feed=1\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" />]]></description>\r\n\t\t\t<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img src=\"http://tctechcrunch.files.wordpress.com/2010/12/googleboring.png\" alt=\"\" /><br />\nBack in April 2008, married couple Aaron and Christine Boring <a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2008/04/04/google-damages-property-values/\">filed suit</a> against Google for &#8220;intentional and/or grossly reckless invasion&#8221; of their privacy, because a Street View car drove down their Private road and snapped some photos of their house.</p>\n<p>Aside from giving the press an opportunity to go pun-crazy, the case has been notable for its longevity: most of the charges, which included negligence, were <a href=\"http://blog.ericgoldman.org/archives/2009/02/google_street_v.htm\">thrown out</a> in February 2009, but Boring v. Google came back for an <a href=\"http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20100201/0410537989.shtml\">encore</a> this year. The lone remaining charge? Trespassing.</p>\n<p>Now, over two and a half years after the case got started, a judge has handed down her consent judgement, ruling that that Google was indeed guilty of Count II Trespass. The Borings are getting a grand total of $1 for their trouble. Ouch.</p>\n<p>In other news related to the case, the Borings tried to appeal to the US Supreme Court (yes, seriously).  The Court <a href=\"http://www.mediapost.com/publications/?fa=Articles.showArticle&amp;art_aid=136988\">turned down</a> the appeal in October.</p>\n<p>This is obviously good news for Google. The case may sound silly, but it could have blown up into a broader examination of Google and online privacy. That didn&#8217;t happen, and given the circumstances (it&#8217;s hard to believe the Borings had their privacy violated in any significant way), that&#8217;s a good thing.</p>\n<p>A Google spokesperson gave us this cheeky statement about the case:</p>\n<blockquote><p>&#8220;We are pleased that this lawsuit has finally ended with plaintiffs&#8217; acknowledgment that they are entitled to only $1.&#8221;</p></blockquote>\n<object id=\"scribd_44493291\" name=\"scribd_44493291\" height=\"500\" width=\"100%\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" data=\"http://d1.scribdassets.com/ScribdViewer.swf\" style=\"outline:none;\" align=\"middle\">\n<param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://d1.scribdassets.com/ScribdViewer.swf\"><param name=\"wmode\" value=\"opaque\"> <param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#ffffff\"> <param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"> <param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\"> <param name=\"FlashVars\" value=\"document_id=44493291&access_key=key-bp8b0y44v06i7u0nshu&page=1&viewMode=list\">\n<embed id=\"scribd_44493291\" name=\"scribd_44493291\" src=\"http://d1.scribdassets.com/ScribdViewer.swf?document_id=44493291&access_key=key-bp8b0y44v06i7u0nshu&page=1&viewMode=list\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" height=\"500\" width=\"100%\" wmode=\"opaque\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"></embed></object>\n<div style=\"font-size:10px;text-align:center;width:100%\"><a href=\"http://www.scribd.com/doc/44493291\">View this document on Scribd</a></div><br />\n<div class=\"cbw snap_nopreview\"><div class=\"cbw_header\"><script src=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/javascripts/widget.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script><div class=\"cbw_header_text\"><a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/\">CrunchBase Information</a></div></div><div class=\"cbw_content\"><div class=\"cbw_subheader\"><a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/company/google\">Google</a></div><div class=\"cbw_subcontent\"><script src=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/cbw/company/google.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script></div><div class=\"cbw_footer\">Information provided by <a href=\"http://www.crunchbase.com/\">CrunchBase</a></div></div></div>\n<br />  <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250299/\"><img alt=\"\" border=\"0\" src=\"http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/tctechcrunch.wordpress.com/250299/\" /></a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://fee